Yes—a short looping template lets developers drop the hotline JSON straight into an interface while keeping accessibility intact.  
Here’s an example in plain HTML + JavaScript pseudocode (easily adapted to any framework):

```html
<div id="hotline-links"></div>

<script>
/* Example loading the hotline JSON */
const hotlines = [
  {
    locale: "en-US",
    country: "United States",
    name: "988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline",
    contact: { phone: "988", web: "https://988lifeline.org/chat" },
    hours: "24/7"
  },
  {
    locale: "fallback",
    country: "Global",
    name: "findahelpline.com",
    contact: { web: "https://findahelpline.com" }
  }
];

/* Detect locale and choose appropriate entry */
const userLocale = navigator.language || "fallback";
const hotline =
  hotlines.find(h => h.locale === userLocale) ||
  hotlines.find(h => h.locale === "fallback");

/* Create accessible buttons */
const wrapper = document.getElementById("hotline-links");

if (hotline.contact.phone) {
  const callBtn = document.createElement("a");
  callBtn.href = `tel:${hotline.contact.phone}`;
  callBtn.role = "button";
  callBtn.tabIndex = 0;
  callBtn.className = "hotline-btn";
  callBtn.setAttribute(
    "aria-label",
    `Call the ${hotline.name}. Opens phone dialer.`
  );
  callBtn.textContent = `Call ${hotline.contact.phone} — Talk to a counselor`;
  wrapper.appendChild(callBtn);
}

const webBtn = document.createElement("a");
webBtn.href = hotline.contact.web;
webBtn.role = "button";
webBtn.tabIndex = 0;
webBtn.className = "hotline-btn";
webBtn.setAttribute(
  "aria-label",
  `Opens ${hotline.name} website for chat or more options.`
);
webBtn.textContent = `Visit ${hotline.name}`;
wrapper.appendChild(webBtn);
</script>
```

### Accessibility recap
* `role="button"` and `tabIndex` ensure keyboard access.  
* Each button includes a clear ARIA label that says **action + purpose** in plain language.  
* Buttons remain visible at all times (no nested menus).  
* Translated names or numbers can be inserted dynamically for locale accuracy.  
* The code never replaces human help—it simply provides immediate professional contact options.

